===Adaptations===
Twenty-six of Leonard's novels and short stories have been adapted for the screen (19 as motion pictures and another seven as television programs).

====Film====
Aside from the short stories already noted, a number of Leonard's novels have been adapted as films, including ''[[Get Shorty]]'' (1990 novel, [[Get Shorty (film)|1995 film]]), ''[[Out of Sight (novel)|Out of Sight]]'' (1996 novel, [[Out of Sight|1998 film]]), and ''[[Rum Punch]]'' (1992 novel, 1997 film ''[[Jackie Brown]]''). ''[[52 Pick-Up]]'' (1986 film) was first adapted very loosely into the 1984 film ''[[The Ambassador (1984 American film)|The Ambassador]]'' (1984), starring [[Robert Mitchum]] and, two years later, under its [[52 Pick-Up|original title]] starring [[Roy Scheider]]. Leonard has also written several screenplays based on his novels, plus original screenplays such as ''[[Joe Kidd]]'' (1972).

The film ''[[Hombre (film)|Hombre]]'' (1967), starring [[Paul Newman]], was an adaptation of Leonard's [[Hombre (novel)|1961 novel of the same name]].

His short story "[[Three-Ten to Yuma]]" (March 1953) and novels ''[[The Big Bounce (novel)|The Big Bounce]]'' (1969) and ''[[52 Pick-Up]]'' have each been filmed twice.

Other novels filmed include:
* ''[[Mr. Majestyk]]'' (with [[Charles Bronson]])
* ''[[Valdez Is Coming]]'' (with [[Burt Lancaster]])
* ''[[52 Pick-Up]]'' (with [[Roy Scheider]])
* ''[[Stick (film)|Stick]]'' (with [[Burt Reynolds]])
* ''[[The Moonshine War]]'' (with [[Alan Alda]])
* ''[[Last Stand at Saber River]]'' (with [[Tom Selleck]])
* ''Gold Coast'' (with [[David Caruso]])
* ''Glitz'' (with [[Jimmy Smits]])
* ''[[Cat Chaser]]'' (with [[Peter Weller]])
* ''[[Out of Sight]]'' ([[George Clooney]], [[Jennifer Lopez]])
* ''[[Touch (1997 film)|Touch]]'' (with [[Christopher Walken]])
* ''Pronto'' (with [[Peter Falk]])
* ''[[Be Cool]]'' (with [[John Travolta]])
* ''[[Killshot (film)|Killshot]]'' ([[Diane Lane]], [[Mickey Rourke]]).
* ''[[Get Shorty (film)|Get Shorty]]'' (with [[John Travolta]])
*[[Freaky Deaky (film)|''Freaky Deaky'']] (with [[Christian Slater]])
* ''[[Life of Crime (film)|Life of Crime]]'' (with [[Jennifer Aniston]]) (based on ''The Switch'')

[[Quentin Tarantino]] has optioned the right to adapt Leonard's novel ''[[Forty Lashes Less One]]'' (1972).<ref>{{cite news|title=Tarantino’s Lost Projects: ’40 Lashes Less One’
|author=Kirk | work=We Are Movie Geeks|date=August 17, 2009|url=http://www.wearemoviegeeks.com/2009/08/tarantinos-lost-projects-40-lashes-less-one/}}</ref><ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3874378/</ref>

====Television====

*In 1992, Leonard played himself in a script he wrote and, with actor Paul Lazar dramatizing a scene from the novel ''Swag'', appeared in a humorous television short about his writing process which aired on the ''Byline Showtime'' series on [[Showtime Networks]].<ref name=IMDb />
*The 2010-15 [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] series ''[[Justified (TV series)|Justified]]'' was based around the popular Leonard character U.S. Marshal [[Raylan Givens]], from the novels ''Pronto'', ''Riding the Rap'', the eponymous ''Raylan'', and the short story "Fire in the Hole".
*The short-lived 1998 TV series ''[[Maximum Bob]]'' was based on Leonard's 1991 novel of the same name. It aired on ABC for seven episodes and starred [[Beau Bridges]].
*The TV series ''[[Karen Sisco]]'' (2003–04) starring [[Carla Gugino]] was based on the U.S. Marshall character from the film ''[[Out of Sight]]'' (1998) played by [[Jennifer Lopez]].
* The 2017 [[Epix]] series  ''[[Get Shorty (TV series)|Get Shorty]]'' is based on the novel of the same.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/get-shortypremiere-date-epix-unveils-photos-chris-odowd-ray-romano-1202094820/|title=‘Get Shorty’ Gets Premiere Date On Epix; Unveils First-Look Photos|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref>

